
The Kubernetes scheduler decides which node a Pod should run on. 
Its most important job is to respect resource requests and limits.

  * requests: The amount of CPU/memory a Pod thinks it will need. 
              The scheduler uses this to find a node that has enough 
              available resources.

  * limits: The maximum amount of CPU/memory a Pod is allowed to use. 
            The kubelet enforces these limits (using cgroups).


These two values determine the Quality of Service (QoS) class of a Pod:




QoS Class    Condition                Behavior under                           Priority
                                      resource pressure         
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Guaranteed   requests == limits for   Last to be evicted                       Highest
             both CPU and memory


Burstable    requests < limits        Evicted before Guaranteed                Medium
             (or only one is set)


BestEffort   No requests or           First to be evicted                      Lowest
             limits set



Understanding this is critical for:

    * Predictable scheduling
    * Avoiding noisy neighbor problems
    * Controlling eviction behavior during node pressure

